<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,1549,2006]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1549,1574]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Disc usually with many scales. Radial shields prominent, half-circle shape. One pair of infradental papillae on the apex of the jaw. Slender arms bearing short, erect and frequently smooth spines. None, one, or two tentacle scales. Muted color patterns. The family is primarily characterized by the oral frame (
<bibRefCitation author="Ljungman, A. V." box="[1245,1431,1621,1646]" journalOrPublisher="Ofversigt af Konglige Vetenskaps-Akademiens Forhandlingar" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="163 - 166" part="1867" refId="ref50311" refString="Ljungman, A. V. (1866) Om nagra nya arter af Ophiurider. Ofversigt af Konglige Vetenskaps-Akademiens Forhandlingar, 1867, 163 - 166." title="Om nagra nya arter af Ophiurider" type="journal article" year="1866">Ljungman 1866</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, L. P." box="[151,307,1657,1682]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of Marine Science" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="623 - 694" part="12" refId="ref54585" refString="Thomas, L. P. (1962) The shallow water amphiurid brittle stars (Echinodermata, Ophiuroidea) of Florida. Bulletin of Marine Science, 12, 623 - 694." title="The shallow water amphiurid brittle stars (Echinodermata, Ophiuroidea) of Florida" type="journal article" year="1962">Thomas 1962</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, A. M." box="[319,448,1657,1682]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Zoology" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="1 - 81" part="19" refId="ref46179" refString="Clark, A. M. (1970) Notes on the family Amphiuridae (Ophiuroidea). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Zoology, 19, 1 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 24085" title="Notes on the family Amphiuridae (Ophiuroidea)" type="journal article" year="1970">Clark 1970</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Tommasi, L. R." box="[459,629,1657,1682]" journalOrPublisher="Contribuicoes Avulsas do Instituto Oceanografico, Universidade de Sao Paulo" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="1 - 146" part="20" refId="ref54902" refString="Tommasi, L. R. (1970) Os ofiuroides recentes do Brasil e de regioes vizinhas. Contribuicoes Avulsas do Instituto Oceanografico, Universidade de Sao Paulo, 20, 1 - 146." title="Os ofiuroides recentes do Brasil e de regioes vizinhas" type="journal article" year="1970">Tommasi 1970</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hendler, G. &amp; Miller, J. E. &amp; Pawson, D. L. &amp; Kier, P. M." bookContentInfo="390 pp." box="[640,860,1657,1682]" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" refId="ref48691" refString="Hendler, G., Miller, J. E., Pawson, D. L. &amp; Kier, P. M. (1995) Sea stars, sea urchins, and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington, 390 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / s 0025315400031568" title="Sea stars, sea urchins, and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean" type="book" year="1995">
Hendler 
<emphasis box="[738,786,1657,1681]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al</emphasis>
. 1995
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Borges, M. &amp; Amaral, A. C. Z." box="[871,1138,1657,1682]" editor="Amaral, A. C. Z." journalOrPublisher="EdUSP, Sao Paulo" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="237 - 272" refId="ref45027" refString="Borges, M. &amp; Amaral, A. C. Z. (2005) Classe Ophiuroidea. In: Amaral, A. C. Z., Rizzo, A. E. &amp; Arruda, E. P. (Eds.), Manual de identificacao dos invertebrados marinhos da regiao sudeste-sul do Brasil. EdUSP, Sao Paulo, pp. 237 - 272." title="Classe Ophiuroidea" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Manual de identificacao dos invertebrados marinhos da regiao sudeste-sul do Brasil" year="2005">Borges &amp; Amaral 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,1549,2006]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1693,1718]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ljungman" authorityYear="1867" box="[344,492,1693,1718]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Amphiuridae</taxonomicName>
is the most diverse family among the Ophiuroidea (
<bibRefCitation author="Stohr, S. &amp; O'Hara, T. &amp; Thuy, B." box="[1091,1302,1693,1718]" journalOrPublisher="PLoS ONE" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="31940" part="7" refId="ref54339" refString="Stohr, S., O'Hara, T. &amp; Thuy, B. (2012 a) Global diversity of brittle stars (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea). PLoS ONE, 7, e 31940. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0031940" title="Global diversity of brittle stars (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea)" type="journal article" year="2012">
Stöhr 
<emphasis box="[1161,1212,1693,1717]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al</emphasis>
. 2012a
</bibRefCitation>
). This large taxon perhaps should be divided into several families. However, it will require a great sampling effort to understand its internal relationships (
<bibRefCitation author="O'Hara, T. D. &amp; Hugall, A. F. &amp; Thuy, B. &amp; Stohr, S. &amp; Martynov, A. V." box="[564,781,1765,1790]" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="415 - 430" part="107" refId="ref52377" refString="O'Hara, T. D., Hugall, A. F., Thuy, B., Stohr, S. &amp; Martynov, A. V. (2017) Restructuring higher taxonomy using broad-scale phylogenomics: The living Ophiuroidea. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 107, 415 - 430." title="Restructuring higher taxonomy using broad-scale phylogenomics: The living Ophiuroidea" type="journal article" year="2017">
O’Hara 
<emphasis box="[657,705,1765,1789]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al</emphasis>
. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
). The high diversity is related to its success in establishing an extended bathymetric range and adapting to a wide variety of environments (
<emphasis box="[1071,1118,1802,1825]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">e.g.,</emphasis>
soft bottoms, rocky shores, and biological substrates) (
<bibRefCitation author="Borges, M. &amp; Amaral, A. C. Z." box="[451,718,1837,1862]" editor="Amaral, A. C. Z." journalOrPublisher="EdUSP, Sao Paulo" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="237 - 272" refId="ref45027" refString="Borges, M. &amp; Amaral, A. C. Z. (2005) Classe Ophiuroidea. In: Amaral, A. C. Z., Rizzo, A. E. &amp; Arruda, E. P. (Eds.), Manual de identificacao dos invertebrados marinhos da regiao sudeste-sul do Brasil. EdUSP, Sao Paulo, pp. 237 - 272." title="Classe Ophiuroidea" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Manual de identificacao dos invertebrados marinhos da regiao sudeste-sul do Brasil" year="2005">Borges &amp; Amaral 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Barboza, C. A. M. &amp; Borges, M." box="[729,1002,1837,1862]" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="1 - 21" part="3447" refId="ref44247" refString="Barboza, C. A. M. &amp; Borges, M. (2012) A checklist of the extant species of ophiuroids (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) from Brazilian waters. Zootaxa, 3447, 1 - 21." title="A checklist of the extant species of ophiuroids (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) from Brazilian waters" type="journal article" year="2012">Barboza &amp; Borges 2012</bibRefCitation>
). Some species voluntarily autotomize the disc during reproduction to aid with the dispersal of gametes (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lyman" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[892,1126,1873,1897]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Amphiodia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="pulchella">
<emphasis box="[892,1126,1873,1897]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Amphiodia pulchella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1852" box="[1141,1380,1873,1897]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Microphiopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="atra">
<emphasis box="[1141,1380,1873,1897]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Microphiopholis atra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Manso et al. 2008))" authorityName="Manso et al." authorityYear="2008" box="[151,692,1909,1934]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Microphiopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis box="[151,430,1909,1933]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Microphiopholis subtilis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Manso, C. L. C. &amp; Alves, O. F. S. &amp; Martins, L. R." box="[452,674,1909,1934]" journalOrPublisher="Biota Neotropica" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="179 - 196" part="8" refId="ref51159" refString="Manso, C. L. C., Alves, O. F. S. &amp; Martins, L. R. (2008) Echinodermata da Baia de Todos os Santos e da Baia de Aratu (Bahia, Brasil). Biota Neotropica, 8, 179 - 196. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 1676 - 06032008000300017" title="Echinodermata da Baia de Todos os Santos e da Baia de Aratu (Bahia, Brasil)" type="journal article" year="2008">
Manso 
<emphasis box="[541,595,1909,1933]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al</emphasis>
. 2008
</bibRefCitation>
))
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1852" box="[711,871,1909,1933]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Microphiopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="gracillima">
<emphasis box="[711,871,1909,1933]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">M. gracillima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also autotomizes it when disturbed and during sublethal predation events (
<bibRefCitation author="Stancyk, S. E. &amp; Golde, H. M. &amp; Pape-Lindstrom, P. A. &amp; Dobson, W. E." box="[482,728,1945,1970]" journalOrPublisher="Marine Biology" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="451 - 462" part="118" refId="ref53985" refString="Stancyk, S. E., Golde, H. M., Pape-Lindstrom, P. A. &amp; Dobson, W. E. (1994) Born to lose. I. Measures of tissue loss and regeneration by the brittlestar Microphiopholis gracillima (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea). Marine Biology, 118, 451 - 462. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / BF 00350302" title="Born to lose. I. Measures of tissue loss and regeneration by the brittlestar Microphiopholis gracillima (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea)" type="journal article" year="1994">
Stancyk 
<emphasis box="[588,645,1945,1969]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al</emphasis>
. 1994
</bibRefCitation>
). They regenerate the disc, however, complicating species identification as a regenerating disc may appear different from an uninjured one (
<bibRefCitation author="Tommasi, L. R." box="[1089,1264,1981,2006]" journalOrPublisher="Contribuicoes Avulsas do Instituto Oceanografico, Universidade de Sao Paulo" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="1 - 146" part="20" refId="ref54902" refString="Tommasi, L. R. (1970) Os ofiuroides recentes do Brasil e de regioes vizinhas. Contribuicoes Avulsas do Instituto Oceanografico, Universidade de Sao Paulo, 20, 1 - 146." title="Os ofiuroides recentes do Brasil e de regioes vizinhas" type="journal article" year="1970">Tommasi 1970</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hendler, G. &amp; Miller, J. E. &amp; Pawson, D. L. &amp; Kier, P. M." bookContentInfo="390 pp." journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" refId="ref48691" refString="Hendler, G., Miller, J. E., Pawson, D. L. &amp; Kier, P. M. (1995) Sea stars, sea urchins, and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington, 390 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / s 0025315400031568" title="Sea stars, sea urchins, and allies: echinoderms of Florida and the Caribbean" type="book" year="1995">
Hendler 
<emphasis box="[1377,1429,1981,2005]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">et al</emphasis>
. 
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,151,213]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
1995). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ljungman" authorityYear="1867" box="[230,378,151,176]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Amphiuridae</taxonomicName>
comprises 506 species distributed across 27 genera (
<bibRefCitation author="O'Hara, T. D. &amp; Hugall, A. F. &amp; Thuy, B. &amp; Stohr, S. &amp; Martynov, A. V." box="[972,1188,152,176]" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="415 - 430" part="107" refId="ref52377" refString="O'Hara, T. D., Hugall, A. F., Thuy, B., Stohr, S. &amp; Martynov, A. V. (2017) Restructuring higher taxonomy using broad-scale phylogenomics: The living Ophiuroidea. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 107, 415 - 430." title="Restructuring higher taxonomy using broad-scale phylogenomics: The living Ophiuroidea" type="journal article" year="2017">
O’Hara 
<emphasis box="[1064,1112,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">et al</emphasis>
. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
). In Brazil, 48 species belonging to 11 genera are recorded (
<bibRefCitation author="Barboza, C. A. M. &amp; Borges, M." box="[568,842,188,213]" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 21" part="3447" refId="ref44247" refString="Barboza, C. A. M. &amp; Borges, M. (2012) A checklist of the extant species of ophiuroids (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) from Brazilian waters. Zootaxa, 3447, 1 - 21." title="A checklist of the extant species of ophiuroids (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) from Brazilian waters" type="journal article" year="2012">Barboza &amp; Borges 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
